 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# 12 — LLM-as-a-Judge Evaluation Framework\n",
    "\n",
    "**Model:** DeepSeek-V3 via Nebius AI Studio  \n",
    "**Pattern:** Systematic Agent Output Evaluation  \n",
    "**Difficulty:** ⭐⭐⭐☆☆\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## The Problem\n",
    "\n",
    "How do you know if your agent is actually good?\n",
    "\n",
    "Human evaluation is expensive and doesn't scale. Traditional NLP metrics (BLEU, ROUGE) don't capture quality for open-ended tasks. **LLM-as-a-Judge** uses a language model as an automated evaluator — scoring outputs on a structured rubric that approximates human judgment.\n",
    "\n",
    "This is the most widely used evaluation method for production LLM applications in 2025, powering systems like AlpacaEval, MT-Bench, and internal evaluation pipelines at major AI labs.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Design Principles for LLM Judges\n",
    "\n",
    "A good judge is:\n",
    "1. **Rubric-based** — scores specific, well-defined criteria (not just \"overall quality\")\n",
    "2. **Position-unbiased** — for pairwise comparisons, doesn't favor the first option\n",
    "3. **Explanation-required** — must justify every score (reduces hallucinated scores)\n",
    "4. **Calibrated** — uses the full scoring range, not just 8-10\n",
    "\n",
    "## Architecture\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "Agent Output(s)\n",
    "     │\n",
    "     ▼\n",
    "[Judge Node] ──── evaluates on rubric ────▶ [Score + Reasoning]\n",
    "     │                                              │\n",
    "     │ (for pairwise)                               ▼\n",
    "     └────────────────────────────────────▶ [Winner Declaration]\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Setup"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import os\n",
    "from dotenv import load_dotenv\n",
    "load_dotenv()\n",
    "\n",
    "from langchain_nebius import ChatNebius\n",
    "from langchain_core.messages import HumanMessage, SystemMessage\n",
    "from langgraph.graph import StateGraph, END\n",
    "from typing import TypedDict, List, Optional, Dict\n",
    "from pydantic import BaseModel, Field\n",
    "\n",
    "# Judge LLM — use low temperature for consistent, reproducible scores\n",
    "judge_llm = ChatNebius(\n",
    "    model=\"deepseek-ai/DeepSeek-V3\",\n",
    "    temperature=0,\n",
    "    api_key=os.environ[\"NEBIUS_API_KEY\"]\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Judge LLM ready.\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Evaluation Rubric\n",
    "\n",
    "We define five criteria. Each criterion is scored independently to:\n",
    "- Make scoring more reliable (simpler questions per call)\n",
    "- Make scores interpretable (you know exactly where an output fails)\n",
    "- Enable targeted improvement (address the lowest-scoring dimension)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "RUBRIC = {\n",
    "    \"accuracy\": {\n",
    "        \"description\": \"Are the facts and claims correct? Are there hallucinations or errors?\",\n",
    "        \"weight\": 0.30\n",
    "    },\n",
    "    \"relevance\": {\n",
    "        \"description\": \"Does the response directly address the question/task? No unnecessary tangents?\",\n",
    "        \"weight\": 0.25\n",
    "    },\n",
    "    \"completeness\": {\n",
    "        \"description\": \"Does the response cover all important aspects of the question?\",\n",
    "        \"weight\": 0.20\n",
    "    },\n",
    "    \"clarity\": {\n",
    "        \"description\": \"Is the response well-structured and easy to read for the target audience?\",\n",
    "        \"weight\": 0.15\n",
    "    },\n",
    "    \"conciseness\": {\n",
    "        \"description\": \"Is the response appropriately concise? Does it avoid unnecessary repetition?\",\n",
    "        \"weight\": 0.10\n",
    "    }\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "assert abs(sum(c[\"weight\"] for c in RUBRIC.values()) - 1.0) < 0.001, \"Weights must sum to 1\"\n",
    "print(f\"Rubric loaded: {list(RUBRIC.keys())}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Pydantic Schemas for Structured Judge Output"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class CriterionScore(BaseModel):\n",
    "    score: float = Field(ge=1.0, le=10.0, description=\"Score from 1-10\")\n",
    "    reasoning: str = Field(description=\"One sentence explaining this score\")\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "class EvaluationResult(BaseModel):\n",
    "    accuracy: CriterionScore\n",
    "    relevance: CriterionScore\n",
    "    completeness: CriterionScore\n",
    "    clarity: CriterionScore\n",
    "    conciseness: CriterionScore\n",
    "    overall_assessment: str = Field(description=\"2-3 sentence summary of strengths and weaknesses\")\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "class PairwiseResult(BaseModel):\n",
    "    winner: str = Field(description=\"'A', 'B', or 'tie'\")\n",
    "    reasoning: str = Field(description=\"Why this response wins\")\n",
    "    a_strengths: str\n",
    "    b_strengths: str"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Part 1: Absolute Scoring\n",
    "\n",
    "Score a single response against the rubric."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "ABSOLUTE_JUDGE_SYSTEM = \"\"\"\n",
    "You are an expert evaluator for AI-generated responses. Your job is to score a response on five criteria.\n",
    "Score each criterion from 1.0 (very poor) to 10.0 (excellent).\n",
    "\n",
    "Criteria definitions:\n",
    "- accuracy: Are facts correct? No hallucinations?\n",
    "- relevance: Does it directly address the question?\n",
    "- completeness: Does it cover all important aspects?\n",
    "- clarity: Is it well-structured and readable?\n",
    "- conciseness: Is it appropriately concise?\n",
    "\n",
    "Be critical and use the full range. A 10 should be rare. A 5 means mediocre but not terrible.\n",
    "Always provide a specific reasoning for each score.\n",
    "\"\"\"\n",
    "\n",
    "absolute_judge = judge_llm.with_structured_output(EvaluationResult)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def evaluate_response(question: str, response: str, context: str = \"\") -> EvaluationResult:\n",
    "    \"\"\"Score a single response against the rubric.\"\"\"\n",
    "    context_section = f\"\\nContext/Reference:\\n{context}\" if context else \"\"\n",
    "\n",
    "    result: EvaluationResult = absolute_judge.invoke([\n",
    "        SystemMessage(content=ABSOLUTE_JUDGE_SYSTEM),\n",
    "        HumanMessage(content=(\n",
    "            f\"Question/Task: {question}{context_section}\\n\\n\"\n",
    "            f\"Response to evaluate:\\n{response}\"\n",
    "        ))\n",
    "    ])\n",
    "    return result\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def compute_weighted_score(result: EvaluationResult) -> float:\n",
    "    \"\"\"Compute the weighted overall score from all criteria.\"\"\"\n",
    "    scores = {\n",
    "        \"accuracy\": result.accuracy.score,\n",
    "        \"relevance\": result.relevance.score,\n",
    "        \"completeness\": result.completeness.score,\n",
    "        \"clarity\": result.clarity.score,\n",
    "        \"conciseness\": result.conciseness.score,\n",
    "    }\n",
    "    return sum(scores[k] * RUBRIC[k][\"weight\"] for k in scores)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def print_evaluation(result: EvaluationResult, label: str = \"Response\"):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Pretty-print an evaluation result.\"\"\"\n",
    "    weighted = compute_weighted_score(result)\n",
    "    print(f\"\\n{'='*60}\")\n",
    "    print(f\"EVALUATION: {label}\")\n",
    "    print(f\"{'='*60}\")\n",
    "    print(f\"Weighted Score: {weighted:.1f}/10.0\")\n",
    "    print()\n",
    "    for criterion, details in RUBRIC.items():\n",
    "        criterion_result = getattr(result, criterion)\n",
    "        bar = \"█\" * int(criterion_result.score) + \"░\" * (10 - int(criterion_result.score))\n",
    "        print(f\"  {criterion.capitalize():<14} [{bar}] {criterion_result.score:.1f}  — {criterion_result.reasoning}\")\n",
    "    print(f\"\\n  Assessment: {result.overall_assessment}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Part 2: Pairwise Comparison\n",
    "\n",
    "Compare two responses head-to-head. This is more reliable than absolute scoring for identifying which of two agents performs better."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "PAIRWISE_JUDGE_SYSTEM = \"\"\"\n",
    "You are an expert evaluator. Compare two AI-generated responses to the same question.\n",
    "Decide which is better (A, B, or tie) based on accuracy, relevance, completeness, clarity, and conciseness.\n",
    "\n",
    "To prevent position bias, focus on content quality, not order.\n",
    "A tie is acceptable when responses are genuinely similar in quality.\n",
    "\"\"\"\n",
    "\n",
    "pairwise_judge = judge_llm.with_structured_output(PairwiseResult)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def compare_responses(question: str, response_a: str, response_b: str) -> PairwiseResult:\n",
    "    \"\"\"Compare two responses head-to-head.\"\"\"\n",
    "    result: PairwiseResult = pairwise_judge.invoke([\n",
    "        SystemMessage(content=PAIRWISE_JUDGE_SYSTEM),\n",
    "        HumanMessage(content=(\n",
    "            f\"Question: {question}\\n\\n\"\n",
    "            f\"Response A:\\n{response_a}\\n\\n\"\n",
    "            f\"Response B:\\n{response_b}\"\n",
    "        ))\n",
    "    ])\n",
    "    return result"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Demo 1: Absolute Evaluation of an Agent Response"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Simulate two responses from different agent configurations\n",
    "question = \"What is Egypt's economic situation and main challenges in 2025?\"\n",
    "\n",
    "response_a = \"\"\"\n",
    "Egypt's economy faces significant headwinds in 2025. After a major IMF-backed reform package,\n",
    "the Egyptian pound stabilized at around 48 EGP/USD following years of currency instability.\n",
    "GDP growth recovered to approximately 4%, supported by remittances ($22 billion annually),\n",
    "tourism revenue (~$13 billion), and Suez Canal receipts (~$9 billion).\n",
    "\n",
    "Key challenges include: high inflation (still above 25% despite declining from a 38% peak),\n",
    "a heavy debt burden (debt-to-GDP ratio near 95%), and persistent youth unemployment.\n",
    "The government's subsidy reform program has squeezed household budgets.\n",
    "Foreign direct investment has been recovering but remains below pre-2016 levels.\n",
    "\"\"\"\n",
    "\n",
    "response_b = \"\"\"\n",
    "Egypt has some economic problems. The currency went down a lot but now it's better.\n",
    "There's inflation and debt. The government is trying to fix things with the IMF.\n",
    "Tourism is important for Egypt's economy. Overall the situation is challenging but improving.\n",
    "\"\"\"\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Evaluating Response A (detailed)...\")\n",
    "result_a = evaluate_response(question, response_a)\n",
    "print_evaluation(result_a, \"Response A (detailed agent)\")\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"\\nEvaluating Response B (vague)...\")\n",
    "result_b = evaluate_response(question, response_b)\n",
    "print_evaluation(result_b, \"Response B (vague agent)\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Demo 2: Pairwise Comparison"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "print(\"\\nRunning pairwise comparison...\")\n",
    "comparison = compare_responses(question, response_a, response_b)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"\\n{'='*60}\")\n",
    "print(\"PAIRWISE COMPARISON RESULT\")\n",
    "print(f\"{'='*60}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Winner: Response {comparison.winner.upper()}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Reasoning: {comparison.reasoning}\")\n",
    "print(f\"\\nA's strengths: {comparison.a_strengths}\")\n",
    "print(f\"B's strengths: {comparison.b_strengths}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Demo 3: Batch Evaluation Summary\n",
    "\n",
    "Simulate evaluating outputs from all agent architectures in this series."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Simulate outputs from different notebooks\n",
    "test_cases = [\n",
    "    {\n",
    "        \"notebook\": \"01 — Self-Critique\",\n",
    "        \"question\": \"Explain why LLMs hallucinate.\",\n",
    "        \"response\": (\n",
    "            \"LLMs hallucinate because they generate statistically probable token sequences \"\n",
    "            \"rather than retrieving verified facts. During training, models learn correlations \"\n",
    "            \"between concepts — but these correlations can lead to plausible-sounding but \"\n",
    "            \"incorrect outputs, especially for obscure topics or questions requiring precise recall. \"\n",
    "            \"Without a ground-truth retrieval mechanism, the model 'fills in gaps' with \"\n",
    "            \"high-probability continuations that may not be accurate.\"\n",
    "        )\n",
    "    },\n",
    "    {\n",
    "        \"notebook\": \"05 — Multi-Agent\",\n",
    "        \"question\": \"Summarize the AI chip market in 2025.\",\n",
    "        \"response\": (\n",
    "            \"NVIDIA dominates the AI chip market in 2025 with ~85% market share in data center GPUs, \"\n",
    "            \"driven by H100/H200 demand and its CUDA software ecosystem. AMD is the primary challenger, \"\n",
    "            \"gaining traction in inference workloads with the MI300X at a 20-30% price advantage. \"\n",
    "            \"Intel's Gaudi 3 has struggled despite competitive benchmarks due to a less mature \"\n",
    "            \"software stack. Enterprise buyers currently prioritize NVIDIA for training and consider \"\n",
    "            \"AMD for cost-sensitive inference deployments.\"\n",
    "        )\n",
    "    },\n",
    "]\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Running batch evaluation...\\n\")\n",
    "batch_results = []\n",
    "\n",
    "for case in test_cases:\n",
    "    result = evaluate_response(case[\"question\"], case[\"response\"])\n",
    "    score = compute_weighted_score(result)\n",
    "    batch_results.append({\"notebook\": case[\"notebook\"], \"score\": score, \"result\": result})\n",
    "    print(f\"  {case['notebook']}: {score:.1f}/10\")\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"\\n\" + \"=\"*60)\n",
    "print(\"BATCH EVALUATION SUMMARY\")\n",
    "print(\"=\"*60)\n",
    "batch_results.sort(key=lambda x: x[\"score\"], reverse=True)\n",
    "for r in batch_results:\n",
    "    bar = \"█\" * int(r[\"score\"]) + \"░\" * (10 - int(r[\"score\"]))\n",
    "    print(f\"  {r['notebook']:<28} [{bar}] {r['score']:.1f}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Key Takeaways\n",
    "\n",
    "| Concept | Implementation |\n",
    "|---------|---------------|\n",
    "| **Rubric-based scoring** | 5 independent criteria with defined weights |\n",
    "| **Structured output** | Pydantic schemas prevent hallucinated/unparseable scores |\n",
    "| **Reasoning required** | Every score includes a justification — catches lazy scoring |\n",
    "| **Pairwise vs absolute** | Pairwise is more reliable for ranking; absolute is better for pass/fail |\n",
    "\n",
    "## Closing Thoughts\n",
    "\n",
    "You've now implemented 12 distinct agentic architectures — from simple reflection loops to 3-tier hierarchies and automated evaluation pipelines.\n",
    "\n",
    "The real learning is in the **tradeoffs**:\n",
    "- More agents = more capability, but more complexity and latency\n",
    "- More context = better grounding, but higher cost and 'lost-in-the-middle' risk\n",
    "- More autonomy = faster execution, but less control\n",
    "\n",
    "**The best architecture is the simplest one that meets your requirements.** Start with a single ReAct agent. Add planning when you need multi-step goals. Add multi-agent only when specialization provides clear value. And always measure — that's what Notebook 12 is for.\n",
    "\n",
    "Happy building. 🚀"
   ]
